model_completion: Mukesh Ambani is the chairman and managing director of Reliance Industries Limited, a Fortune 500 company. He is the richest man in India, with a net worth of $22.7 billion. Mukesh Ambani was born in 1957 in Aden, Yemen. His father, Dhirubhai Ambani, was a businessman who started Reliance Industries in 1966. Mukesh Ambani attended Stanford University, where he earned a bachelor's degree in chemical engineering. He then went to Yale University, where he earned a master's degree in business administration. Mukesh Ambani is married to Nita Ambani, and they have two children.

Massimo Vignelli was born in Milan, Italy in 1931. He studied architecture at the Politecnico di Milano and the University of Venice. In 1958, he moved to the United States and worked as an architect. In 1960, he founded the Vignelli Associates, a design firm. In 1965, he designed the New York City subway map, which is still in use today. He also designed the American Airlines logo, the Bloomingdale's logo, and the Ford logo. Massimo Vignelli died in 2014.

Freddie Mercury was born in Zanzibar, Tanzania, in 1946. He was the lead singer of the rock band Queen. Mercury was a flamboyant performer, and his stage presence was a major part of Queen's success. He died in 1991 from AIDS.

Socrates was a Greek philosopher who lived from 469 BC to 399 BC. He was a student of the philosopher Sophroniscus, and later became a teacher himself. Socrates was known for his philosophical method, which was based on asking questions. He was also known for his moral integrity, and was a critic of the Athenian democracy. Socrates was sentenced to death for corrupting the youth of Athens, and was executed by drinking poison.

Elie Wiesel was born in Sighet, Romania, on September 30, 1928. He was a Romanian-American writer, professor, political activist, Nobel Laureate, and Holocaust survivor. Wiesel was the author of 57 books, including the memoir 'Night,' which describes his experiences during the Holocaust. He was awarded the Nobel Peace Prize in 1986.

Robin Williams was born in Chicago, Illinois in 1951. He was raised in a Catholic family, and his father was a senior executive at Ford Motor Company. Williams attended the University of California, Berkeley, and later moved to San Francisco to pursue a career in comedy. He began his career as a stand-up comedian, and later became a successful actor. He is best known for his roles in the films 'Good Morning, Vietnam,' 'Mrs. Doubtfire,' and 'Good Will Hunting.' He has won several awards, including an Academy Award, a Grammy Award, and a Golden Globe Award. He died in 2014.

Amartya Sen is an Indian economist and philosopher. He was born in 1933 in India. He is a Nobel Prize winner, and is known for his work on welfare economics, social choice theory, and economic and social justice. He is a professor at Harvard University, and has also taught at the University of Oxford, and the University of California, Berkeley. He has written several books, including 'Development as Freedom,' 'The Argumentative Indian,' and 'Identity and Violence.'

Isadore Sharp is the founder and chairman of Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts. He was born in Toronto, Canada in 1931. Sharp graduated from the University of Toronto with a degree in economics. He then worked as a salesman for a hotel chain. In 1961, he opened the first Four Seasons Hotel in Toronto. The hotel was a success, and Sharp opened more hotels in the United States and Canada. Today, Four Seasons Hotels and Resorts is one of the largest hotel chains in the world.

Elizabeth Blackwell was born in Bristol, England, in 1821. She was the first woman to receive a medical degree in the United States. She graduated from Geneva Medical College in 1849. She then opened a medical practice in New York City, where she became a pioneer in women's health. She was also a social reformer, and she was a strong supporter of women's rights. She died in 1910.

Nobu Matsuhisa was born in 1949 in Japan. He moved to the United States in 1967, and worked as a sushi chef in Los Angeles. In 1987, he opened his first restaurant, Matsuhisa, in Beverly Hills. In 1993, he opened his second restaurant, Nobu, in New York. Nobu has since expanded to 30 locations around the world.

Larry Page was born in 1973 in East Lansing, Michigan. He attended the University of Michigan, where he met Sergey Brin. In 1998, they founded Google, and Page became the CEO of the company in 2001. Page is also the co-founder of Google X, a research and development company.

Winona LaDuke is an American activist, environmentalist, and writer. She is the founder of the White Earth Land Recovery Project, a Native American organization that works to protect the environment and promote sustainable development. LaDuke is also the founder of the Indigenous Women's Network, a group that works to empower Native American women. She is the author of several books, including 'Last Standing Woman: The Life of Winona LaDuke,' 'All Our Relations: Native Struggles for Land and Life,' and 'The Militarization of Indian Country.' LaDuke was the Green Party's vice presidential candidate in the 1996 and 2000 elections.

Greta Gerwig is an American actress, director, and screenwriter. She was born in Sacramento, California, and grew up in New York City. Gerwig attended Barnard College, where she majored in English and Theater. She began her acting career in 2007, and has since appeared in films such as 'Frances Ha,' 'Mistress America,' and 'Lady Bird.' Gerwig has also directed films such as 'Frances Ha' and 'Lady Bird.' In 2017, she was nominated for an Academy Award for Best Director for 'Lady Bird.'

José Mujica was born in 1935 in Montevideo, Uruguay. He was a member of the Tupamaros, a left-wing guerrilla group, and was imprisoned for 14 years. He was elected president of Uruguay in 2010, and is the current president of Uruguay. He is known for his simple lifestyle, and has donated most of his salary to charity.

Hideki Matsuyama is a Japanese professional golfer. He was born in 1992 in Ehime Prefecture, Japan. Matsuyama turned professional in 2010. He won the 2010 Japan Amateur Championship, and the 2010 Asia-Pacific Amateur Championship. In 2011, he won the Japan Golf Tour Championship, and the Japan Open. In 2012, he won the Japan Golf Tour Championship, and the Japan Open. In 2013, he won the Japan Golf Tour Championship, and the Japan Open. In 2014, he won the Japan Golf Tour Championship, and the Japan Open. In 2015, he won the Japan Golf Tour Championship, and the Japan Open. In 2016, he won the Japan Golf Tour Championship, and the Japan Open.

Alex Morgan is an American soccer player. She was born in 1989 in San Dimas, California. She is a forward for the Orlando Pride of the National Women's Soccer League, and the captain of the United States women's national soccer team. She was the youngest player to score in the Women's World Cup in 2011. She was also the youngest player to score in the Olympic Games in 2012. She was named the 2012 FIFA Women's World Player of the Year.

Born in 1797, Sojourner Truth was a former slave who became a prominent abolitionist and women's rights activist. She was born Isabella Baumfree, and was sold into slavery at the age of nine. She escaped in 1826, and became a preacher. In 1843, she changed her name to Sojourner Truth, and became a prominent speaker for the abolitionist movement. She was also a suffragist, and spoke out against racial discrimination. She died in 1883.

Elon Musk was born in South Africa in 1971. He moved to Canada at the age of 17, and then to the United States in 1989. He studied at the University of Pennsylvania and the Wharton School of Business. In 1995, he co-founded Zip2, a web software company. In 2002, he co-founded PayPal, an online payment company. In 2003, he co-founded SpaceX, a private space exploration company. In 2006, he co-founded Tesla Motors, an electric car company. In 2012, he co-founded SolarCity, a solar energy company. In 2015, he co-founded OpenAI, a non-profit artificial intelligence research company.

Cindy Sherman was born in 1954 in Glen Ridge, New Jersey. She is an American photographer and film director. Sherman is known for her conceptual portraits, in which she is the subject. She has been called the "high priestess of the art world." Sherman's work has been exhibited in museums around the world, and she has won numerous awards, including the MacArthur Fellowship in 1995.

Katie Couric was born in 1957 in Arlington, Virginia. She is a journalist and television personality. Couric was the first female solo anchor of a network evening news program. She was the co-host of the Today Show from 1991 to 2006, and the host of the CBS Evening News from 2006 to 2011. She is currently the host of the daytime talk show Katie.

Bad Bunny is a Puerto Rican rapper and singer. He was born in San Juan, Puerto Rico in 1994. He is known for his songs "Soy Peor" and "Diles." Bad Bunny has collaborated with artists such as Daddy Yankee, Ozuna, and Maluma. He has also collaborated with Cardi B on the song "I Like It."

Esther Duflo is a French-American economist and the co-founder of the Abdul Latif Jameel Poverty Action Lab (J-PAL). She is the first woman to win the John Bates Clark Medal, which is awarded to the most promising American economist under the age of 40. She is also the youngest person to win the prize. Duflo was born in Paris, France, in 1972. She received her Ph.D. in economics from MIT in 2000. She is currently a professor of economics at MIT and a professor of economics at the Paris School of Economics. She is also the co-founder of the Abdul Latif Jameel Poverty Action Lab (J-PAL).

Richard Pryor was born in Peoria, Illinois, on December 1, 1940. He was raised by his grandmother, and his mother was a prostitute. Pryor started performing stand-up comedy in 1963, and he became a popular comedian in the 1970s. He was known for his vulgar and controversial humor. Pryor was diagnosed with multiple sclerosis in 1986, and he died on December 10, 2005.

Tex Avery was born in Taylor, Texas, in 1908. He was a cartoonist and animator, and is considered one of the most influential animators of all time. Avery was the creator of the popular cartoon character, 'Bugs Bunny.' He also created 'Droopy,' 'Screwy Squirrel,' and 'Tweety Bird.' Avery died in 1980.

Dave Chappelle was born in 1973 in Ohio. He is a comedian, actor, and writer. He is best known for his sketch comedy show, 'Chappelle's Show,' which aired on Comedy Central from 2003 to 2006. He has also appeared in several movies, including 'Half Baked,' 'Blue Streak,' and 'The Nutty Professor.' In 2005, he left his show and moved to South Africa. He returned to the United States in 2013.

Zaha Hadid was born in Baghdad, Iraq in 1950. She studied architecture at the American University of Beirut and the Architectural Association School of Architecture in London. In 1980, she established her own architectural firm, Zaha Hadid Architects. She is the first woman to win the Pritzker Architecture Prize, and the first woman to be awarded the Royal Institute of British Architects' Gold Medal. She has designed many buildings, including the London Aquatics Centre for the 2012 Summer Olympics, the Guangzhou Opera House in China, and the Heydar Aliyev Center in Azerbaijan. Zaha Hadid died in 2016.

Mary Wollstonecraft was born in 1759 in Spitalfields, London. She was the daughter of a weaver and a dressmaker. She was educated at home by her mother. In 1778, she married William Godwin, a philosopher and political writer. They had a daughter, Fanny, in 1784. In 1792, Wollstonecraft published her first book, 'A Vindication of the Rights of Woman.' She died in 1797, at the age of 38, from complications during childbirth.

Warren Buffett was born in 1930 in Omaha, Nebraska. He is the CEO of Berkshire Hathaway, a company he founded in 1965. Buffett is one of the richest people in the world, with a net worth of $72.7 billion. He is also one of the most successful investors in the world, and is known as the "Oracle of Omaha." He is a philanthropist, and has donated billions of dollars to charity.

George Carlin was born in 1937 in New York City. He was a comedian, actor, and writer. Carlin was known for his stand-up comedy, which often included political and social commentary. He was also known for his "Seven Dirty Words" routine, which was banned from radio and television. Carlin died in 2008.

Quentin Tarantino was born in 1963 in Los Angeles, California. He is a film director, screenwriter, and actor. Tarantino's first film was 'Reservoir Dogs,' which was released in 1992. His next film, 'Pulp Fiction,' was released in 1994, and won the Palme d'Or at the Cannes Film Festival. Tarantino's other films include 'Jackie Brown,' 'Kill Bill,' and 'Django Unchained.'

Simone Biles is an American gymnast. She is the first woman to win four all-around titles at the World Artistic Gymnastics Championships. She is also the first woman to win three consecutive world all-around titles. Biles was born in 1997 in Columbus, Ohio. She started gymnastics at the age of six. In 2013, she won the all-around title at the World Artistic Gymnastics Championships. She also won the gold medal in the team event. In 2014, she won the all-around title at the World Artistic Gymnastics Championships for the second time. She also won the gold medal in the team event. In 2015, she won the all-around title at the World Artistic Gymnastics Championships for the third time. She also won the gold medal in the team event. In 2016, she won the all-around title at the World Artistic Gymnastics Championships for the fourth time.

Novak Djokovic was born on May 22, 1987, in Belgrade, Serbia. He is a professional tennis player, and is currently ranked as the world's number one player. He has won 12 Grand Slam singles titles, and has won three Australian Open titles, two Wimbledon titles, and one US Open title. He has also won the ATP World Tour Finals three times. In 2011, he was named the ATP World Tour Player of the Year.

Born in Russia in 1905, Ayn Rand was a Russian-American novelist, philosopher, playwright, and screenwriter. She is best known for her novels 'The Fountainhead' and 'Atlas Shrugged.' Rand's philosophy, Objectivism, has influenced many libertarians and conservatives. She died in 1982.

Rumi was born in 1207 in Balkh, Afghanistan. He was a Persian poet, jurist, theologian, and Sufi mystic. Rumi's father was a scholar and a religious leader. Rumi's father died when he was only eight years old. Rumi was married at the age of 20, and he had a son. Rumi's son died in 1231, and Rumi became a dervish. Rumi's poetry is still popular today. He died in 1273.

Born in Romania in 1876, Constantin Brâncuși was a Romanian sculptor who is considered to be one of the most influential sculptors of the 20th century. He is best known for his abstract sculptures, which are characterized by their simplicity and geometric shapes. Brâncuși's most famous works include 'Bird in Space' and 'The Kiss.' He died in 1957.

James Watt was born in 1736 in Greenock, Scotland. He was an inventor and engineer, and is best known for his improvements to the steam engine. Watt's father was a shipwright, and Watt was apprenticed to a shipbuilder at the age of 14. He later became a mathematical instrument maker, and in 1763, he was hired by the University of Glasgow to repair scientific instruments. In 1765, Watt was hired by Matthew Boulton to work on a steam engine. Watt's improvements to the steam engine made it more efficient, and he patented his invention in 1769. Watt's steam engine was used in factories and mills, and it helped to fuel the Industrial Revolution. James Watt died in 1819.

Christiaan Barnard was born in 1922 in South Africa. He was a cardiac surgeon and the first person to perform a heart transplant. In 1967, Barnard performed the first human heart transplant on Louis Washkansky. Barnard was knighted in 1976 and was awarded the Nobel Prize in Medicine in 1983. He died in 2001.

Jorge Mario Bergoglio was born on December 17, 1936, in Buenos Aires, Argentina. He was ordained as a priest in 1969, and became the Archbishop of Buenos Aires in 1998. In 2013, he was elected as the 266th Pope of the Catholic Church, and took the name Pope Francis. He is the first Pope from the Americas, and the first Jesuit Pope. Pope Francis is known for his humility, and his concern for the poor. He has been a strong advocate for social justice, and has called for the Catholic Church to be more inclusive.

Tina Fey was born in 1970 in Upper Darby, Pennsylvania. She is an American actress, comedian, writer, and producer. Fey is best known for her work on the television series 'Saturday Night Live' and '30 Rock.' She has also appeared in several films, including 'Mean Girls,' 'Baby Mama,' and 'Date Night.' Fey is the creator, writer, and star of the television series '30 Rock.' She has won several awards, including the Primetime Emmy Award for Outstanding Lead Actress in a Comedy Series, and the Golden Globe Award for Best Actress in a Television Series Musical or Comedy.

Samuel Morse was born in 1791 in Massachusetts. He was a painter and inventor. In 1832, he invented the telegraph, which was a device that sent messages over wires. In 1844, he sent the first telegraph message, which was "What hath God wrought?" Samuel Morse died in 1872.
